### 1. One-Line Summary
G-1 is a spin-focused, high-grip ESN-style rubber with a safer arc and clearer dwell, while Dynaryz AGR is a more direct, speed-and-counter oriented rubber that rewards aggressive timing and compact strokes.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** G-1 is calmer and easier to keep short with light touch, while Dynaryz AGR tends to feel livelier and “jumps” more off the racket on small inputs.
    * **Top End:** Dynaryz AGR generally has a higher top-end pace on full swings and punchy contact, while G-1 tops out lower but is easier to access consistently.
    * **Linearity:** G-1 is more linear and predictable across gears; Dynaryz AGR is more “on/off” and benefits from committed acceleration.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** G-1 is typically easier for opening against backspin due to grip + dwell + arc; Dynaryz AGR can open strongly too, but usually asks for cleaner brushing and forward commitment.
    * **Max Spin:** G-1 tends to produce heavier spin when you brush and engage the topsheet fully; Dynaryz AGR can reach high spin, but leans more toward speed/spin balance than pure rotation.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** G-1 usually feels tack-free but very grippy and confidence-inspiring on brush contact; Dynaryz AGR feels grippy yet more “crisp,” with less of that prolonged grab.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** G-1 is generally medium-high throw with a higher arc; Dynaryz AGR is typically lower and more forward/direct.
    * **Safety:** G-1 offers more net clearance and rally safety on topspin exchanges; Dynaryz AGR demands better timing/angle control but gives a more penetrating trajectory.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** G-1 feels more elastic and “connected” to the ball; Dynaryz AGR feels firmer/crisper with a punchier rebound.
    * **Dwell:** G-1 provides more dwell for shaping the ball; Dynaryz AGR has shorter dwell, favoring quick contact and fast transitions.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** G-1 is more sensitive to incoming spin when you leave the racket passive, but its dwell helps you actively manage spin; Dynaryz AGR can feel less “grabby” on passive contact yet is bouncier, so depth control can be trickier.
    * **Touch Play:** G-1 is usually easier for drop shots, short pushes, and stop blocks; Dynaryz AGR rewards practiced hands but can pop the ball long if your touch is not precise.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Dynaryz AGR is typically more stable and efficient for passive blocks because of its direct rebound; G-1 is workable but benefits from a slightly more active block to control trajectory.
    * **Active Counter:** Dynaryz AGR shines on punch blocks, counter-drives, and fast re-counters; G-1 counters well too, but emphasizes spin-based countering over pure pace.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose G-1 if:**
    * You prioritize heavy spin, safer arc, and confident opening loops.
    * You want clearer dwell/feedback for developing technique and shaping shots.
    * Your game leans on topspin variation, third-ball loop, and controlled rally building.

* **Choose Dynaryz AGR if:**
    * You prioritize direct speed, quick rebound, and pressure through counters/blocks.
    * You like compact, aggressive timing close-to-mid distance.
    * Your style is more hit/counter oriented and you can manage the bouncier short game.